{"title_page": "Camille Cottin", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{short description|French film, television and stage actress}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Camille Cottin\n| image              = Camille Cottin janvier 2016.jpg\n| alt                =\n| caption            = Cottin in January 2016.\n| birth_name         =\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|1978|12|1|df=y}}\n| birth_place        = [[Paris]], [[France]]\n| death_date         =\n| death_place        =\n| nationality        = [[France|French]]\n| occupation         = [[Actress]]\n| years_active       = 2001\u2013present\n| credits            = ''La Connasse''<br />''Call My Agent!''\n| television         = [[Canal+]]\n| children           = 2\n}}\n'''Camille Cottin''' ({{IPA-fr|kamij k\u0254t\u025b\u0303|lang}}) (born 1 December 1978) is a [[France|French]] [[film actress|film]], [[television actress|television]] and [[stage actress]]. She became well-known in 2013 for playing her role in the series of comedy sketches of ''La Connasse'' on channel [[Canal+]].\n\n== Life and career ==\nCamille Cottin was born in [[Paris]], but spent her teenage years in [[London]] before returning to France, where she became a high school English teacher. At the same time, she took classes at a theater and dramatic art school and then with the company \"Th\u00e9\u00e2tre du Voyageur\". She played small roles in many films and television series. In 2009, she joined the \"Troupe \u00e0 [[Pierre Palmade|Palmade]]\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.lemonde.fr/culture/article/2013/11/15/camille-cottin-les-mots-pour-deplaire_3514642_3246.html |title=Camille Cottin, les mots pour d\u00e9plaire |author=Olivier Dumons |work=[[Le Monde]] |date=15 November 2013 |accessdate=26 March 2014 |language=fr}}</ref> She appeared the same year in an advertisement for a Japanese telephone, directed by [[Wes Anderson]] with [[Brad Pitt]], with music by [[Serge Gainsbourg]] with the song \"[[Poup\u00e9e de cire, poup\u00e9e de son]]\" sung by [[France Gall]].\n\nIn 2013, she played the main role in ''La Connasse'' on [[Canal+]] produced by Silex Films, a series consisting of sketches in [[candid camera]] of less than two minutes each. Written by [[No\u00e9mie Saglio]] and \u00c9lo\u00efse Lang, the episodes were broadcast on ''[[Le Grand Journal (Canal+)|Le Grand Journal]]'' and became available on DVD from 4 March 2014.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.lesinrocks.com/2014/03/08/actualite/camille-cottin-la-connasse-enfant-11480678/ |title=Camille Cottin: La Connasse est comme une enfant |author=Carole Boinet |work=[[Les Inrockuptibles]] |date=8 March 2014 |accessdate=26 March 2014 |language=fr}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.metronews.fr/culture/canal-camille-cottin-une-sacree-connasse/mncb!fiexMgVbTYXBE/ |title=Camille Cottin, une sacr\u00e9e ''Connasse'' |author=Sonia Ouadhi |date=2 March 2014 |accessdate=26 March 2014 |language=fr}}</ref> She later appeared in the film based on the series titled ''[[Connasse, Princesse des c\u0153urs]]'', released in 2015.\n\nIn 2015, Cottin played the lead role of agent Andr\u00e9a Martel in ''[[Dix pour cent]]'' (''Call My Agent!''), a television series which ran for three seasons that was first broadcast on [[France 2]] and which later enjoyed wide international distribution on [[Netflix]]; Cottin won a Best Actress ACS Award for her role. In 2016, Cottin appeared in ''[[Allied (film)|Allied]]'', ''[[Iris (2016 film)|Iris]]'', and ''Cigarettes et chocolat chaud.''\n\n== Personal life ==\nCamille Cottin is the daughter of the artist [[Gilles Cottin]]. She married an architect in 2005 and they have two children: a son born in 2009,<ref>\n{{Cite web |url=http://www.gqmagazine.fr/pop-culture/medias/articles/un-rencard-avec-la-connasse-de-canal-/12610 |title=Un rencard avec la connasse de Canal |work=[[GQ (magazine)|GQ Magazine]] |date=23 October 2013 |language=fr}}</ref>\nand a daughter born in August 2015.<ref>\n{{cite news\n|language=en\n|title=Sa fille s'appelle Anna - Camille Cottin maman pour la deuxi\u00e8me fois\n|newspaper=[[Paris Match]]\n|date=10 October 2015\n|url=http://www.parismatch.com/People/Television/Camille-Cottin-maman-pour-la-deuxieme-fois-Sa-fille-s-appelle-Anna-Tele-7-Jours-France-2-10-843441\n|access-date = 15 April 2017}}</ref>\nHer great-grandfather is the historian [[Paul Cottin]].\n\n==Filmography==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Director\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 2001\n| ''[[Yamakasi (film)|Yamakasi]]''\n|\n| [[Ariel Zeitoun]] & Julien Seri\n|\n|-\n| 2002\n| ''Hep Taxi !''\n|\n| Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric Berthe\n| TV Mini-Series\n|-\n| 2005\n| ''Tango Overlord''\n| Young French woman\n| Fran\u00e7ois Choquet\n| TV Short\n|-\n| rowspan=3| 2006\n| ''Odile...''\n| The woman\n| B\u00e9n\u00e9dicte Delg\u00e9hier\n| Short\n|-\n| ''P.J.''\n| Annabelle\n| Claire de la Rochefoucauld\n| TV Series (1 Episode)\n|-\n| ''Femmes de loi''\n| The victim\n| \u00c9tienne Dhaene\n| TV Series (1 Episode)\n|-\n| 2007\n| ''La commune''\n| Albane Devlay\n| Philippe Triboit\n| TV Series (1 Episode)\n|-\n| 2008\n| ''P.J.''\n| Mina Ferlet\n| Pierre Leix-Cote\n| TV Series (1 Episode)\n|-\n| 2009\n| ''Le probl\u00e8me avec Tom''\n| Anne\n| Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric Ramade\n| Short\n|-\n| 2010\n| ''Fracture''\n| Slimane's neighbor\n| Alain Tasma\n| TV Movie\n|-\n| 2011\n| ''Bernard & Fils, suicideurs \u00e0 domicile''\n| The woman\n| Avril Besson\n| Short\n|-\n| rowspan=3| 2012\n| ''Il \u00e9tait une fois, une fois''\n| Juliette's mother\n| Christian Merret-Palmair\n|\n|-\n| ''Mon troquet''\n|\n| Louis Delva\n| Short\n|-\n| ''Le jour o\u00f9 tout a bascul\u00e9''\n| Annick\n| Pierre-Fran\u00e7ois Brodin\n| TV Series (1 Episode)\n|-\n| rowspan=3| 2013\n| ''Pep's''\n| Marina Trufaine\n| St\u00e9phane Kopecky\n| TV Series (1 Episode)\n|-\n| ''Vaugand''\n| A woman\n| [[Charlotte Brandstr\u00f6m]]\n| TV Series (1 Episode)\n|-\n| ''Ma meuf''\n| Sophie\n| Edo